[1
Date: Wed, 12 Jan 2000 21:59:11 +0100
From: Wolfgang Preiser <W.Preiser@em.uni-frankfurt.de>

The following is my translation from the news site of the state-wide
German television channel, ZDF, as of 12 Jan 2000, approx. 9 p.m.
local time (GMT + 1). Additions in brackets are mine.
News text:
Case of Lassa fever in Wurzburg (northern part of Bavaria, Germany)
Female student ill after holiday -- No risk for population
A 23-year old female student being treated in a (Wuerzburg)
hospital has contracted Lassa fever, a dangerous tropical disease, after
a holiday in Africa. The Bavarian Ministry of Health says she is in a
serious state.
The woman was admitted with flu-like symptoms to a hospital in
Schwdbisch Hall (another town in southern Germany), says the director of
the local health department, Konrad Klaess. After seven days as
an in-patient there her doctors were convinced she was suffering from a
tropical disease. During Monday night she was therefore transferred to
the Tropical Medicine Department of the Wuerzburg hospital. Laboratory
investigations had confirmed the suspicion of Lassa fever.
We took the clinical suspicion very serious from the start, said
Klaess. Measures for isolation were taken immediately. In Wuerzburg the
woman is being treated in a separate intensive care unit. The hospital
and the health department in Schwdbisch Hall were informed...
The health departments in Baden-Wuerttemberg (the
county that Schwdbisch Hall is situated in) are currently investigating
with whom the 23-year old has been in contact since her return from West
Africa. According to first results she has not met relatives or friends.
Call to passengers on the flight
The infected woman arrived on 7 Jan 2000 on Air Portugal flight number
TP 5576 in Frankfurt am Main, says the Ministry for Social Affairs of
Baden-Wuerttemberg. All passengers are urgently requested to contact
their local health departments. If symptoms such as fever above 38.5
degrees C, headache, sore throat, coughing and intestinal discomfort
occur they should present to a hospital. The hotline of the state health
administration is 0711 / 1849328 or 0170 / 2230815.
According to experts the student does not pose a risk to the population.
"People who met her by chance are at virtually zero risk", says the
spokesperson for the Robert Koch-Institut, Edgar Muschketat. "We will
not get a Lassa epidemic in Germany, for the virus is very difficult to
transmit." The Bavarian health minister Barbara Stamm (CSU, ruling
party) declares that any threat to the population of Bavaria and
particularly Wuerzburg can be ruled out. In Wuerzburg the patient had only
been in contact with medical personnel.
Lassa fever, which occurs predominantly in Nigeria (sic!),
according to information from the health department leads to severe internal
bleeding. Even with inpatient treatment 20 percent of cases will be
fatal.
12. January 2000
With material from: AP/DPA
--
My comments (W. Preiser):
- Situation seems to be under control, one single case;
- the Wuerzburg Tropical Medicine Dept. is a good and knowledgeable one
and deserves confidence in dealing with such cases correctly.
- They do not say how the diagnosis was confirmed but have had five
days, and thus time to send specimens e. g. to the Bernhard
Nocht-Institut in Hamburg (Prof. Schmitz)
- Remember the panic last summer with the cameraman in Berlin who was
suspected of suffering from Ebola but had (and died from) yellow fever,
apparently unvaccinated.
--
