[2
Date: Sat, 8 Jan 2000 04:38:54 +0100
From: "Wolfgang PREISER" <preiser@wildmail.com>

Translation from the website of the Missionsarztliche Klinik in
Wuerzburg (Wuerzburg Mission Hospital) 12 Jan 2000 12 p.m.
http://www.uni-wuerzburg.de/missio/klinik/lassa.html

Patient with Lassa fever on the isolation unit of the Wuerzburg
Mission Hospital
Situation on 12 Jan 2000 at 4.00 p.m. (local time, GMT +1)
The (female) patient is in the meantime isolated in the second
intensive care unit of the Mission Hospital which is exclusively for
her use. In this part in the far end of the building she is under
optimal care with all intensive medical measures and facilities and a
volunteer medical and nursing team. The patients state is relatively
good, according to the circumstances. The high fever continues, there
is respiratory compromise and disturbed haemostasis.
For patients at the Mission Hospital in all its departments there is
no risk, for the patient is isolated in a separate part of the
building and there is no connection between her room and all other
facilities through ventilation ducts or other ducts.
The authorities in Bavaria and in Baden Wuerttemberg have been
informed and are collaborating closely with the medical teams in the
surveillance of contact persons.
The specific antiviral agent Ribavirin is available in sufficient
quantities.
Prof. Dr. med. K. Fleischer, Head of Tropical Medicine Department
D. Radler, Chief Executive of Mission Hospital (Missionsärztlichen
Klinik gGmbH)
***
[3
Date: 12 Jan 2000
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Agence France Presse Wed 12 Jan 2000 [edited

Doctors were fighting Wednesday to save the life of a 23-year-old German
woman sick with Lassa fever after a trip to West Africa.
The student, who returned to Germany on 1 Jan 2000, fell ill two days
later and is now in serious condition, the Bavarian health ministry
said.
Lassa fever, named after a Nigerian village, was first identified in
1969. It is virus-borne and causes fatal haemorrhaging in 40 percent of
cases.
The art student, who was not identified, spent from November until
the end of December 1999 in Ghana and Ivory Coast on a student exchange
programme. The ministry said she was treated for a week in her local
hospital
for a high fever, before being transferred to a clinic in Wuerzburg
with suspected malaria when her condition worsened. The Hamburg Institute of
Tropical Medicine confirmed the diagnosis of Lassa fever on Wednesday.
